    l1c204q16: {
      rightno: option3,
      question:
        "Formula of heat of reaction static pressure & static volume, \u0394H = ?",
      attribute:
        "Qₚ = The amount of heat applied, \u0394E = Altered internal gas energy, V = Volume of gas, \u0394n = Altered mole numbers, R = The ideal gas constant, T = Temperature in Kelvin",
      op1: "\u0394H = E + \u0394nRT",
      op2: "\u0394H = \u0394nRT / \u0394E",
      op3: "\u0394H = \u0394E + \u0394nRT",
      op4: "\u0394H = nRT/E",
      proof:
        "\n\n If, the value of the applied heat is Qₚ, the increase in internal energy is \u0394E and the work of increasing the volume of the gas is P\u0394V, then \n\n Qₚ = \u0394E + P\u0394V......(\u2170) \n\n We know that, Qₚ = \u0394E + P\u0394V \n\n = E₂ - E₁ + P(V₂ - V₁) \n\n = E₂ - E₁ + PV₂ - PV₁ \n\n = (E₂ + PV₂) - (E₁ + PV₁) \n\n We also know that, Enthalpy, H = E + PV \n\n Under static pressure, (E₁ + PV₁) = H₁ and (E₂ + PV₂) = H₂, So, Qₚ = \u0394H......(\u2171) \n\n From (\u2170) and (\u2171) can be written that, \n\n \u0394H = \u0394E + P\u0394V = \u0394E + p(V₂-V₁) = \u0394E + PV₂ - PV₁ \n\n From the ideal gas equation, PV = nRT \n\n So, \u0394H = \u0394E + n₂RT - n₁RT = \u0394E + RT (n₂ - n₁) n\n Again, \u0394H = \u0394E + \u0394nRT",
      pic: "",
      picon: false,
      picproof: "",
    },

