      proof:
        "\n\n Suppose that the vertices of the triangle ABC are A (x₁, y₁), B (x₂, y₂) and C (x₃ y₃); The midpoints of the sides BC, CA and AB are D, E, F. Now if we draw the median AD, BE, CF, they will intersect at the point G. The point G is called the center of gravity of the triangle and it divides each median in the ratio 2: 1.  \n\n Now the coordinates of the midpoint D of BC is ((x₂ + x₃)/2   ,(y₂ + y₃)/2) \n\n Suppose, the coordinates of G (x, y), ∵ AG : GD = 2 : 1 \n\n ∴ x = 2 . (x₂ + x₃)/2 + 1 . (x₁)/(2 + 1) =  (x₁ + x₂ + x₃)/3 \n\n and, y = 2 . (y₂ + y₃)/2 + 1 . (y₁)/(2 + 1) = (y₁ + y₂ + y₃)/3 \n\n Thus, the center of gravity of ABC = ( ( x¹+ x²+ x³)/3 )   ,(y¹+ y²+ y³)/3)) \n\n Suppose that the vertices of the triangle ABC are A (x₁, y₁), B (x₂, y₂) and C (x₃ y₃); The midpoints of the sides BC, CA and AB are D, E, F. Now if we draw the median AD, BE, CF, they will intersect at the point G. The point G is called the center of gravity of the triangle and it divides each median in the ratio 2: 1. Now the coordinates of the midpoint D of BC is ((x₂ + x₃)/2   ,(y₂ + y₃)/2)",
