        "\n\n ∠A is right angle in first figure and ∠A is obtuse angle in second figure. Suppose, the center of the perpendicular circle of the triangle ABC is 0 and the radius is R. As shown in Fig. 3, ABC is a right triangle and in this case line BD coincides with BC. Now we get from the first and second figure, BD = 2R and ∠BCD = 90. Thus, from BCD triangle sin∠BDC = BC/BD  = a/2R  ... (i) \n Whereas, according to the first figure, ∠BCD = ∠A and according to the second figure ∠BCD = π - A \n Therefore, in both cases sin∠BDC = sinA \n Now according to the third figure, BD = a 	i.e., 2R = a or, a/1  = 2R. \n So, in each case we get, a/sin⁡A = 2R \n Similarly, adding A, O will extend the circumference of the circle to the point E. Now adding C, E and B, E respectively shows that, \n b/(sinB) = 2R and c/sin⁡C  = 2R . Therefore, we get, a/sin⁡A = b/(sinB) = c/(sinC) = 2R",
