      op4: "cosA = (b²  + c²  – a²)/2bc , cosB= (c²  + a²  – b²)/2ca , cosC= (a² + b² – c²)/2ab ",
      proof:
        "\n\n Let's draw the AD perpendicular on the BC arm [first figure]. Suppose CD = x and AD = h \n From the ADC triangle h² = b² - x \n From the ADB triangle h² =  c²- (a - x)² \n ∴  b² - x² = c² - (a - x)² = b² = c² - a² + 2ax ... (i) Again from the ACD triangle,  x/b= cosC That is, x = bcosC \n ∴ From (i) we get, b² = c² - a² + 2ab cosC. \n = cosC = a² + b² - c²/2ab \n Let's draw the AD perpendicular on the extension of the BC calf [Figure 2]. From the ADC triangle h² = b² - x \n From the ADB triangle, h² = c² - (a + x)² \n ∴ b² - x² = c² - (a+x)² = b² = c² - a² - 2ax ... (i) \n Again from the ACD triangle,  x/b  = cos(180° - C) = -cosC, That is, x = -bcosC \n ∴ From (i) to b² = c² - a² + 2abcosC [setting value to x] \n = cosC = (a²+ b²- c²)/2ab \n When, C = 90°, the formula will be, c = a + b  [The Pythagorean theorem] \n That is, a² + b² - c² = 2ab cos C ∴ cos C = (a² + b² - c²)/2ab \n So, from any kind of triangle cos C = (a² + b² - c²)/2ab \n Similarly, cosA = (b² + c² - a²)/2bc and cosB = (c² + a²- b²)/2ca formula can be established.",
