        "\n\n We know, E = (1/4πϵ₀K) × (q/r²) \n dV = Force on a single positive charge × the component of the movement towards the force \n = E × dr cos180° [Since the force E and the dr are opposite to each other, their inclusion angle is 180°] \n So, dV = - Edr \n or,  dV = - (1/4πϵ₀K) × (q/r²) dr \n By adding we get, ∫₀ⱽ = - ∫ʳ∞ (1/4πϵ₀K) × (q/r²) dr \n = - (q/4πϵ₀K) ∫ʳ∞ dr/r² \n [V]ⱽ₀ = - (q/4πϵ₀K) × [-1/r]ʳ∞ \n Or, V - 0 = - (q/4πϵ₀K) × [-1/r + 1/∞] \n Or, V = (1/4πϵ₀K) × q/r \n If, K = 1 [If the medium is air or empty] \n Then, \n V = (1/4πϵ₀) × (q/r)",
