  op4: "x = asinθ and y = bcosθ",
  proof: "Substituting x = a tanθ and y = b secθ into the equation y²/b² - x²/a² = 1 gives:\n\nb²(sec²θ)/(b²/a²) - a²(tan²θ) = a² - b²\n\nDividing both sides by a²b² gives:\n\n(sec²θ)/(b²/a²) - (tan²θ)/(a²/b²) = 1/(a²b²)\n\nUsing the trigonometric identity tan²θ = sec²θ - 1 and substituting, we get:\n\n(sec²θ)/(b²/a²) - ((sec²θ) - 1)/(a²/b²) = 1/(a²b²)\n\nMultiplying both sides by (a²/b²) gives:\n\n(sec²θ) - (a²/b²)(sec²θ) + (a²/b²) = 1/(a²b²)\n\nRearranging gives:\n\n(a² + b²)sec²θ - b² = a²(1 + 1/(a²b²))\n\nsec²θ = (a²/b²)(1/((a² + b²) - 1))\n\nSubstituting the value of secθ obtained above into the expressions for x and y gives:\n\nx = a tanθ and y = b secθ = a(1/(sqrt(a²/b² - 1)))\n\nThis is the parametric equation of the hyperbola.",
